member.returns:
            The subsets of the list. For example, if the input array is { 1, 2, 3 }, the output
            should be as follows:


{ 1 }

{ 2 }

{ 3 }

{ 1, 2 }

{ 1, 3 }

{ 2, 3 }

{ 1, 2, 3 }

            7 cases (without null set) in total.

member.summary:
Creates a  instance that iterates on each element.
Different with the default iteration operation, this type will iterate each element by reference,
in order that you can write the code like:

foreach (ref int element in new[] { 1, 3, 6, 10 })
{
    Console.WriteLine(++element);
}

member.param:
The options on deserialization. The argument cannot be 
when the argument  is not ;
otherwise, a  will be thrown.

member.remarks:
You can use this type like this:

var sb = new StringHandler(initialCapacity: 100);

sb.Append("Hello");
sb.Append(',');
sb.Append("World");
sb.Append('!');

Console.WriteLine(sb.ToStringAndClear());

Due to the design of the C# feature "s in interface",
we suggest you use explicit implementation to implement this property, and makes the value
referencing to the field that is named Default.
Here is an example code to describe the above words:

// The static read-only field to introduce the default value.
public static readonly T Default = default(T);

// An explicit implementation on the default-value property.
static T IDefaultable<T>.Default => Default;

